In TypeScript, you can use a technique called "type narrowing" to specify that a value can have multiple types but that you know it will only have one of those types in a particular scenario. Here's an example:

```
function processValue(value: string | number) {
  if (typeof value === 'string') {
    // TypeScript will now know that 'value' is of type 'string'
    // and you can use string-specific methods and properties
  } else if (typeof value === 'number') {
    // TypeScript will now know that 'value' is of type 'number'
    // and you can use number-specific methods and properties
  }
}
```

In this example, the function takes a parameter of type `string | number`, which means it can be either a string or a number. The `if` statement checks the type of the `value` parameter and sets up a conditional block where TypeScript knows that the `value` parameter is of type `string`. The `else if` statement does the same for the case where `value` is a number.

This technique is useful when you need to perform different actions based on the type of a value, but you want TypeScript to know the specific type in each branch of your conditional.

Here's a basic template for a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  string word; // the word to search for
  int count = 0; // the count of occurrences

  // open the file for reading
  ifstream file("input.txt");

  // read the file line by line
  string line;
  while (getline(file, line)) {
    // split the line into words
    string words[100];
    int num_words = split(line, ' ', words, 100);

    // search for the word in the words array
    for (int i = 0; i < num_words; i++) {
      if (words[i] == word) {
        count++;
      }
    }
  }

  cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" appears " << count << " times in the file." << endl;

  return 0;
}

// split a string into words and store them in an array
int split(const string &s, char delim, string words[], int max_words) {
  int num_words = 0;
  size_t start = 0, end = 0;
  while ((end = s.find(delim, start)) != string::npos) {
    if (num_words >= max_words) {
      break;
    }
    words[num_words] = s.substr(start, end - start);
    num_words++;
    start = end + 1;
  }
  if (start < s.length()) {
    words[num_words] = s.substr(start);
    num_words++;
  }
  return num_words;
}
```

In this program, we use `ifstream` to read the input file line by line. We split each line into words using `split`, and then search for the target word in each word. The count of occurrences is updated accordingly. Finally, we print the result to the console.

To use this program, you need to replace `"input.txt"` with the name of your input file and set `word` to the specific word you want to search for.
